To create a mod for Minecraft in Java, you will need to use the Minecraft Forge modding platform. This platform provides a set of tools and APIs that allow you to create custom behavior for Minecraft.

To implement a block that causes the player to float when they stand on it, you will need to do the following:

1. Create a new class that extends the `Block` class from the Minecraft Forge API. This class will define the properties and behavior of your custom block.
2. In the `Block` class, you will need to override the `onEntityWalk` method. This method is called whenever an entity (such as a player) walks on top of the block.
3. In the `onEntityWalk` method, you can use the `entity.addVelocity` method to add a upward velocity to the entity. This will cause the entity to start moving upward, simulating the effect of floating.

Here is an example of how this might be implemented in code:
```
public class FloatingBlock extends Block {
    public FloatingBlock() {
        // Set the properties of the block, such as its material, hardness, and resistance to explosions.
    }

    @Override
    public void onEntityWalk(World world, BlockPos pos, Entity entity) {
        // Add an upward velocity to the entity to make it float.
        entity.addVelocity(0, 0.5, 0);
    }
}
