Sure, here's an example Java program that reads a TSV file in parallel using the Java 8 Stream API and the Fork/Join framework for parallel processing:
```java
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Paths;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinPool;

public class TsvFileReader {

  public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
    // Change the file path to your TSV file
    String filePath = "path/to/your/tsv/file.tsv";

    // Read the lines of the file in parallel
    List<String> lines = Files.lines(Paths.get(filePath))
        .parallel()
        .collect(Collectors.toList());

    // Process the lines in parallel using a Fork/Join pool
    ForkJoinPool pool = new ForkJoinPool();
    pool.submit(() -> {
      lines.parallelStream().forEach(line -> {
        // Do something with each line of the TSV file
        System.out.println(line);
      });
    }).get();
  }
}
```
In this example, we use the `Files.lines()` method to read the lines of the TSV file in parallel, and then use a Fork/Join pool to process each line in parallel. The `parallel()` method is called on the stream to enable parallel processing, and the `collect()` method is used to collect the lines into a list.

Note that this example assumes that the TSV file is small enough to fit into memory. If your TSV file is very large, you may want to use a streaming approach to avoid loading the entire file into memory at once. One way to do this is to use a `BufferedReader` to read the file line by line, and then use the `parallel()` method on the stream of lines to enable parallel processing.

